INSERT INTO public.om_activity_years (activity_code, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, ba, sag_short_code, title, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$OM_NAVY_X_514$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$OM_NAVY$$, NULL, NULL, $$Department of the Navy$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$, 4A1M
                                                                                                                                                                          (Page 6 of 22)
                                                                                Department of the Navy
                                                                        FY 2027 President's Budget Submission
                                                                          Operation and Maintenance, Navy
                                                             Budget Activity: Administration and Servicewide Activities
                                                                         Activity Group: Servicewide Support
                                                                     Detail by Subactivity Group: Administration
Pentagon and other federal agencies. The RRMC has emergency operations centers for the military branches and other federal agencies. The RRMC conducts full-scale COOP
exercises to test procedures for relocating personnel and integrating functions. The RRMC is a key part of the U.S. national defense strategy, enabling government operations to
continue after a nuclear attack or natural disaster.

The Financial Improvement and Audit Remediation (FIAR) program provides the DON the resources to meet FY 2024 National Defense Authorization Act (Sec. 1005)
requirement which mandates all Department of War (DoW) components obtain an unmodified financial statement audit opinion by FY 2028. Audits are rigorous examinations of
Navy's business environment. Corrective actions lead to improved transparency of resource usage and improved asset accountability. To date, the Navy has made substantial
progress on its audit roadmap, which highlights interdependencies between business processes and needed system improvements and documents the path to achieving an
unmodified audit opinion by FY 2028. Continued audit success requires documentation, testing and standardization of business processes related to the recording and reporting of
financial transactions. Auditability, once achieved, must be sustained into the future to include building the appropriate infrastructure in Navy-Marine Corps organizations to
monitor and test financial and cyber security internal controls regularly. The requested FIAR resources will enable the DON to establish the capability to simultaneously respond to
current audits, remediate deficiencies, and sustain an audit ready business and operations environment, thus keeping the DON on the trajectory to obtain an unmodified audit
opinion in FY 2028 or sooner - ultimately heightening warfighter readiness and lethality.

Defense Finance and Accounting Service (DFAS) provides the DON finance and accounting services, including delivering accurate, timely, and reliable financial reports and
information while monitoring, managing, and continuously providing appropriate quality control over data. Specific services provided to the DON include; Civilian Pay
Operations, Military Pay Operations, Contract Payments, Travel Payments, Commercial Payments, Debt Services, Garnishments, Support to Others, Accounting Services, and
Financial Management Systems operations and maintenance. DFAS also provides the DON professional audit readiness, response, and sustainment services that are in accordance
with Service Provider responsibilities outlined in the Office of the Under Secretary of War (Comptroller) (OUSW(C)) FIAR Guidance, Office of Management & Budget (OMB)
Circular A-123 and associated federal statutes that govern internal control compliance.

The Mass Transit Benefit Program (MTBP), administered under DODI 1000.27, is available to eligible civilian employees and military service members as permitted by law and
regulation. Its goals are to reduce pollution and traffic congestion, preserve the environment, and expand transportation options. Participants in the National Capital Region (NCR)
receive subsidies covering their personal commuting costs, up to the monthly limit set by Congress.

The Navy Travel Service Fee is a centralized management fee paid to the contracted vendor for official commercial travel services provided to all Navy personnel.

The National Archives and Records Administration (NARA) fee is for the U.S. Navy and the USMC document storage and services bill. The NARA bill provides decorations for
veterans since the Cold War era; and pays for Navy and USMC veterans' records retrieval, review, and replacement.


Other programs financed in this sub-activity group include Medical Headquarters, Overseas Banking, Navy Medical Travel, American Forces Radio and Television Service
(AFRTS) (Site TV), Environmental Conservation and Compliance, Alcohol Abuse Prevention and Reports, Alcohol and Drug Management Information System (ADMITS),
Exceptional Family Member Program (EFMP), Total Sailor Fit to Fight (TSFTF), Foreign Military Sales (FMS), Suicide Prevention, Operational Stress Control, and the
Commander Fleet Forces Command Security Cooperation.




