        Common Aviation Command and Control System Afloat and SACC Automation to support cyber security requirements and
        integration with Marine Corps systems. It also provides a modest increase for the Planning and Decision Aid System (PDAS)
        to support an expanded scope of program management and engineering activities, ensuring our warfighters have the
        specialized tools they need for mission success. (Baseline: $68,358)
      xxvi)Terrestrial Networks: increase makes a critical investment in our Long Haul Circuits, the terrestrial data highways that        1,648
        form the backbone of the global naval network. This funding directly supports the expansion of bandwidth across the Defense
        Information Systems Network (DISN), as mandated by the Defense Information System Agency (DISA). This enhancement
        ensures our network has the capacity to support NGEN upgrades and meet the ever-increasing data transport demands of the
        modern fleet. (Baseline: $268,656)
      xxvii)Electronic Warfare & Countermeasures: increase reflects a clear modernization strategy, where funding is prioritized for       1,528
        the installation and sustainment of the advanced MK-59 Decoy Launching System. This increase is offset by planned
        reductions in the sustainment of older, legacy systems like the Active NULKA decoy and early variants of the AN/SLQ-32,
        focusing our resources on the most effective technologies. (Baseline: $66,477)
      xxviii)Electronic Warfare & Countermeasures: increase strategically invests in accelerating the readiness of the AN/SLQ-             1,299
        32(V)6 and funding the installation of the advanced MK-59 decoy system. This critical modernization is funded through a
        deliberate reduction in the recertification and repair of older, less capable legacy decoys. This prioritization ensures our
        surface fleet is equipped with superior self-defense technology to better counter modern anti-ship missile threats. (Baseline:
        $17,338)
      xxix)Cross-Cutting Technical Support: increase makes a targeted investment in Real Time Spectrum Operations (RTSO). This             1,289
        funding will enhance the sustainment of our Own Force Monitoring antenna hardware and improve our infrastructure for
        health and status reporting of critical C4I systems. This investment is essential for maintaining situational awareness of the
        electromagnetic environment and ensuring our forces can operate effectively in a congested and contested spectrum.
        (Baseline: $25,484)
      xxx)CIVPERS: Cooperative Engagement Capability (CEC) increase provides for the transition out of a middle of tier                     691
        acquisition program and into an ACT II program which necessitates a corresponding increase in acquisition workforce. This

