  based analysis of what works and what does not. It sustains the enterprise-level readiness reporting systems that provide commanders with an authoritative picture of our
  warfighting health. The analysis derived from these programs allows our tactical leaders to identify capability gaps, validate effective solutions, and provide data-driven
  recommendations back to the doctrine developers, ensuring the lessons learned by the fleet today become the winning tactics of tomorrow.

II. Force Structure Summary:

Doctrine & Combat Tactics Development

The Warfare Development Centers (WDCs): This funding provides for the manning and operations of the Navy's five engines of tactical innovation, whose doctrine and expertise
directly support every operational unit in the Navy:
             Navy Warfare Development Command (NWDC)
             Naval Aviation Warfighting Development Center (NAWDC)
             Naval Surface and Mine Warfare Development Center (SMWDC)
             Undersea Warfighting Development Center (UWDC)
             Naval Information Warfighting Development Center (NIWDC)

Advanced Tactical Training

Fleet Training Commands: This funding sustains the two commands responsible for advanced, integrated fleet training:
             Commander, Strike Group Four (CSG-4): Trains and certifies all East Coast and Forward Deployed Naval Forces.
             Commander, Carrier Strike Group Fifteen (CSG-15): Trains and certifies all West Coast naval forces.

Deploying Naval Forces: The training delivered by CSG-4 and CSG-15 prepares and certifies the Navy's entire rotational force, including 11 Carrier Strike Groups and 7
Amphibious Ready Groups.

The Navy Continuous Training Environment (NCTE): This funding sustains the network infrastructure that connects all deploying units and over 19 globally distributed training
sites into a single, virtual battlespace for high-end training.

Ranges, Targets, & Experimentation

Fleet Ranges and Exercise Support: Provides for the operation and sustainment of the critical "arenas" where the fleet hones its skills. This supports exercises for 3 Carrier Strike
Groups, 3 Amphibious Ready Groups, and 7 Surface Action Groups annually. Key supported infrastructure includes:
             Pacific Missile Range Facility (PMRF)
             Tactical Training Ranges (TTR) at Fallon, Cherry Point, and Yuma
             Jacksonville Shallow Water Training Range (JSWTR)
             Southern California (SOCAL) Anti-Submarine Warfare Range

The Marine Corps Expeditionary Force: Directly supports the advanced training and readiness of the Marine Air-Ground Task Force (MAGTF). This funding is critical for major
exercises such as:
