2)Program Increases                                                                                                                                    422,416
  a)Program Increase in FY 2027                                                                                                                        422,416
      i)Operational and Engineering Support; increase to fund additional support needed to safely and reliably maintain the strategic       85,364
         weapon system (SWS). Significant aging concerns for nuclear weapons demand proactive intervention to mitigate emerging
         risks. These age-related challenges, if left unaddressed, could lead to component failure, decreased reliability, and potential
         impacts on system safety. This increase reflects support for amplified efforts focused on performance evaluation, problem
         investigation, energetics aging surveillance, and safety assessments. Additional emphasis is focused on missile subsystem
         with expanded efforts for the Life Extension Device Signature Analysis testing program to extend component service life.
         These efforts curtail unacceptable operational risk by detecting and mitigating adverse impacts while ensuring continued
         SWS deployment for the fleet. (Baseline: $1,005,300)
      ii)Administration, Conventional Prompt Strike, and Missile Processing; increase for the critical need of an additional 444 full-      82,293
         time civilian personnel (FTE) to ensure the on-time delivery of the nation's highest-priority nuclear modernization and
         strategic deterrence programs. This workforce growth is essential to support Secretary of War's priorities and posture
         programs such as Trident II D5LE2, W93/Mk7 warhead and reentry body, CPS, and Sea Launched Cruise Missile-Nuclear
          (SLCM-N) for mission success, while safely maintaining the aging D5LE deployed missile. While the program has achieved
          efficiency gains through aggressive workforce optimization and is currently significantly exceeding FY 2026 budgeted
          initial projections, the sheer scale and complexity of concurrent modernization efforts require this targeted expansion. This
          increase continues a proven, multi-year workforce development strategy that has successfully grown the program's talent
          base, to include targeted recruitment, retention, and relocation incentives to attract the highly specialized scientific and
          engineering expertise required for these unique national security programs. This investment is essential to sustaining the
          credibility of the nation's nuclear deterrent for decades to come. (Baseline: $548,852; +444 civilian FTE)
      iii)Operational and Engineering Support; increase to fund Strategic Weapon System (SWS) maintenance and sustainment in                57,382
         order to alleviate the compounded impact of inflation on the program and increased costs for material, transportation, and
         labor. The SWS is sustained by long-standing, trusted industry partners with a specialized workforce trained to develop,
         sustain, and dispose of nuclear weapons. The aerospace and defense sector typically experiences inflation rates that outpace
         the typical national average. This financial pressure threatens the viability of these critical partners and the highly skilled
         workforce that is essential to the SWS program. This increase mitigates the unacceptable risk of losing essential suppliers,
